QUICK SETUP INSTRUCTIONS:

These instructions are for base mongodb (mongo, mongod, mongos, mongoperf).  I have recreated from my history file and memory â€” so you should review carefully â€” and LMK if you have any issues

â€“ check for mongodb user

grep mongodb /etc/passwd

â€“ if NO mongodb user, create:

sudo adduser --ingroup nogroup --shell /etc/false --disabled-password --gecos "" \
--no-create-home mongodb

â€“ cd to the directory with mongo, mongod, mongos, etc
â€“ ensure appropriate owner & executable permissions
â€“ strip out symbols to reduce file size
â€“ move to /usr/bin which is in PATH

cd dir-with-binaries
sudo chown root:root mongo*
sudo chmod 755 mongo*
sudo strip mongo*
sudo cp -p mongo* /usr/bin

â€“ create log file directory with appropriate owner & permissions

sudo mkdir /var/log/mongodb
sudo chown mongodb:nogroup /var/log/mongodb

â€“ create the DB data directory with convenient access perms

sudo mkdir /var/lib/mongodb
sudo chown mongodb:root /var/lib/mongodb
sudo chmod 775 /var/lib/mongodb

â€“ create the mongodb.conf file in /etc

cd /etc
sudo vi mongodb.conf

â€“ insert into file:

# /etc/mongodb.conf
# minimal config file (old style)
# Run mongod --help to see a list of options

bind_ip = 127.0.0.1
quiet = true
dbpath = /var/lib/mongodb
logpath = /var/log/mongodb/mongod.log
logappend = true
storageEngine = mmapv1

â€“ create systemd / service entry

cd /lib/systemd/system
sudo vi mongodb.service

â€“ insert into file:

[Unit]
Description=High-performance, schema-free document-oriented database
After=network.target

[Service]
User=mongodb
ExecStart=/usr/bin/mongod --quiet --config /etc/mongodb.conf

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target

â€“ you are now ready to launch mongodb!

sudo service mongodb start

â€“ check status

sudo service mongodb status

â€“ MAKE SURE YOU SHUTDOWN CLEANLY!

sudo service mongodb stop

Please LMK if you have issues and/or success in using these binaries  and instructions ðŸ˜Ž

MongoDB Tools install:

unzip the tools tar file after downloading into an empty directory (download link described above).  Strip out symbols to reduce size, change owner and permissions, and move to /usr/bin directory:

tar zxvf tools_mongodb.tar.gz
sudo strip mongo*
sudo chown root:root mongo*
sudo chmod 755 mongo*
sudo mv mongo* /usr/bin

You can now invoke tools from the command line â€” mongodump, mongoimport, etc.